### Trend

Looking at our data points (- means too small or N/A):

| N | Matcher Time (s) | Growth Rate (compared to previous N) | Verifier Time (s) |  Growth Rate (compared to previous N) |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | 0.002204 | - | 0.001303 | - |
| 2 | 0.007583 | - | 0.001395 | - |
| 4 | 0.008967 | - | 0.007997 | - |
| 8 | 0.009004 | - | 0.007124 | - |
| 16 | 0.009300 | - | 0.007440 | - |
| 32 | 0.008673 | - | 0.008266 | - |
| 64 | 0.011054 | 1.2 |  0.008842 | 1.1 |
| 128 | 0.016651 | 1.5 | 0.010774 | 1.2 |
| 256 | 0.028884 | 1.7 | 0.021537 | 2.0 |
| 512 | 0.078741 | 2.7 | 0.053673 | 2.5 |
| 1024 | 0.282086 | 3.6 | 0.167052 | 3.1 |

We can see that our data is approaching a growth rate of 4x. This relationship means that our data is approaching a **<ins>relationship with O(n^2)</ins>** because each data point is close to 4 times larger than the one before it. With a low value of N, python overhead takes a majority of the computation time, meaning that each lower N data point is not measureable for growth rate because of the overhead dominates runtime.